2 SENATE BILL 742
1 who lost eligibility under certain circumstances; and generally relating to
2 determinations of eligibility for home– and community–based services.
3 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
4 Article – Health – General
5 Section 7–309(b)
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
8 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
9 Article – Health – General
10 Section 15–101(a), (h), and (i)
11 Annotated Code of Maryland
12 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
13 BY adding to
14 Article – Health – General
15 Section 15–103.9
16 Annotated Code of Maryland
17 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
18 Preamble
19 WHEREAS, The landmark decision of the U.S. Supreme Court in Olmstead v. L.C.
20 ex rel. Zimring, 527 U.S. 581 (1999) affirmed that unjustified segregation of individuals
21 with disabilities constitutes discrimination in violation of Title II of the federal Americans
22 with Disabilities Act; and
23 WHEREAS, The Olmstead decision established that people with disabilities have
24 the right to receive services in the most integrated setting appropriate to their needs and
25 that states must provide community–based services when such services are appropriate,
26 desired by the individual, and can be reasonably accommodated; and
27 WHEREAS, Individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities are vital
28 members of Maryland’s communities, contributing meaningfully in workplaces, classrooms,
29 places of worship, neighborhoods, and civic life across the State; and
30 WHEREAS, The State of Maryland has demonstrated a longstanding commitment
31 to community inclusion by closing nearly all large public institutions for people with
32 intellectual and developmental disabilities and investing in supports that allow
33 Marylanders with disabilities to live, work, and thrive in the communities of their choosing,
34 with people they choose; and
35 WHEREAS, Despite this progress, barriers remain when administrative
36 inefficiencies and delays in Medicaid eligibility determinations or redeterminations cause
37 individuals to lose critical home– and community–based services or remain
38 institutionalized after they are medically ready for discharge; and

SENATE BILL 742 3
1 WHEREAS, Ensuring timely Medicaid eligibility determinations, preventing
2 procedural terminations, and protecting continuity of home– and community–based
3 services coverage are necessary to fulfill the promise of Olmstead and uphold Maryland’s
4 commitment to dignity, inclusion, and equality for all people with disabilities; and
5 WHEREAS, Maryland law requires the Developmental Disabilities Administration
6 and the Department of Disabilities to compile statewide and regional data from written
7 plans of habilitation, including barriers to community placement, and to incorporate the
8 data annually into the State’s Olmstead Plan together with recommendations for
9 addressing those barriers; now, therefore,
10 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
11 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
12 Article – Health – General
13 7–309.
14 (b) (1) An individual receiving Administration services who receives notice
15 from the Department that the individual has lost eligibility to receive Maryland Medical
16 Assistance Program services [shall have 90 days after the date on which the notification
17 letter was mailed to] MAY appeal the determination.
18 (2) If an individual appeals a loss of eligibility within the time period
19 required under [paragraph (1) of this subsection] § 42 C.F.R. 431.231, Administration
20 services for the individual shall continue uninterrupted until the outcome of the appeal is
21 complete.
22 (3) The Department shall ensure that providers of Administration services
23 to an individual affected by a loss of eligibility are notified of the individual’s loss of
24 eligibility when notice is sent to the individual.
25 (4) The Department shall ensure that providers, including coordinators of
26 community services, have the ability to automatically exchange electronic data with the
27 Department through an application program interface with the Department’s Long Term
28 Services and Supports software system.
29 15–101.
30 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
31 (h) “Program” means the Maryland Medical Assistance Program.
32 (i) “Program recipient” means an individual who receives benefits under the
33 Program.

4 SENATE BILL 742
1 15–103.9.
2 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
3 INDICATED.
4 (2) “EX PARTE REDETERMINATION” MEANS A PROCESS BY WHICH
5 THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO
6 CONTINUE TO RECEIVE SERVICES USING EXISTING DATA, WITHOUT REQUIRING THE
7 PROGRAM RECIPIENT TO SUBMIT ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.
8 (3) “HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES” MEANS SERVICES
9 AUTHORIZED UNDER A MEDICAID STATE PLAN OPTION OR WAIVER UNDER § 1115
10 OR § 1915(C), (I), OR (K) OF THE FEDERAL SOCIAL SECURITY ACT.
11 (4) “PROCEDURAL DISENROLLMENT” MEANS THE TERMINATION OF A
12 PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO RECEIVE SERVICES BASED ON REASONS
13 RELATED TO THE RENEWAL PROCESS AND NOT ON A DETERMINATION OF
14 INELIGIBILITY.
15 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL COMPLY WITH THE REQUIREMENTS OF 42
16 C.F.R. § 435.912 RELATED TO THE TIMELY DETERMINATION AND
17 REDETERMINATION OF PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY, INCLUDING PROCESSING AN
18 APPLICATION:
19 (1) IF A DETERMINATION OF DISABILITY IS NOT REQUIRED, WITHIN
20 45 DAYS AFTER THE RECEIPT OF THE APPLICATION; AND
21 (2) IF A DETERMINATION OF DISABILITY IS REQUIRED, WITHIN 90
22 DAYS AFTER THE RECEIPT OF THE APPLICATION.
23 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL CONDUCT EX PARTE REDETERMINATIONS
24 AND USE ALL PROCEDURES AUTHORIZED UNDER 42 C.F.R. § 435.916 TO PREVENT
25 PROCEDURAL DISENROLLMENT OF INDIVIDUALS RECEIVING HOME– AND
26 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES.
27 (D) IN ACCORDANCE WITH 42 C.F.R. § 435.905 AND SUBJECT TO
28 SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE, IN
29 ELECTRONIC AND PAPER FORMATS, AND ORALLY AS APPROPRIATE AN
30 ACCOMMODATION, THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION TO ALL APPLICANTS AND OTHER
31 INDIVIDUALS ON REQUEST:
32 (1) REQUIREMENTS FOR PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY;

SENATE BILL 742 5
1 (2) AVAILABLE PROGRAM SERVICES; AND
2 (3) THE RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES OF APPLICANTS AND
3 PROGRAM RECIPIENTS.
4 (E) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE THE INFORMATION
5 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION IN PLAIN LANGUAGE AND IN A
6 MANNER THAT IS TIMELY AND ACCESSIBLE TO INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE:
7 (I) LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENT THROUGH THE PROVISION
8 OF LANGUAGE SERVICES, INCLUDING ORAL INTERPRETATION AND WRITTEN
9 TRANSLATIONS, AT NO COST TO THE INDIVIDUAL; OR
10 (II) LIVING WITH DISABILITIES THROUGH THE PROVISION OF
11 AUXILIARY AIDS AND SERVICES AT NO COST TO THE INDIVIDUAL IN ACCORDANCE
12 WITH THE FEDERAL AMERICANS WITH DISABILITIES ACT AND § 504 OF THE
13 FEDERAL REHABILITATION ACT OF 1973.
14 (2) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE TAGLINES IN NON–ENGLISH
15 LANGUAGES TO INFORM INDIVIDUALS OF:
16 (I) THE AVAILABILITY OF THE ACCESSIBLE INFORMATION AND
17 LANGUAGE SERVICES UNDER THIS SECTION; AND
18 (II) HOW TO ACCESS THE INFORMATION AND SERVICES.
19 (F) IF THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES THAT THE INFORMATION
20 NECESSARY TO CONFIRM A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO CONTINUE TO
21 RECEIVE SERVICES IS INCOMPLETE, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL CONTINUE TO
22 PROVIDE THE HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES AND OTHER SERVICES
23 UNDER THE PROGRAM UNTIL THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT HAS EXHAUSTED ALL DUE
24 PROCESS RIGHTS AND A FINAL DETERMINATION IS ISSUED.
25 (G) (1) IF A PROGRAM RECIPIENT IS PROCEDURALLY DISENROLLED
26 FROM HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES DUE TO A FAILURE BY THE
27 DEPARTMENT TO REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER AFTER THE
28 RECIPIENT HAS TIMELY RETURNED INFORMATION REQUIRED UNDER 42 C.F.R. §
29 435.916(B)(2)(1)(B) AND 42 C.F.R. § 435.952(C) AND THE DELAY IN THE
30 REDETERMINATION WAS NO FAULT OF THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT, THE
31 DEPARTMENT SHALL REINSTATE THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY AND THE
32 PROVISION OF HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES AND AUTHORIZE

6 SENATE BILL 742
1 ENROLLMENT RETROACTIVELY TO THE DATE OF DISENROLLMENT PENDING THE
2 DEPARTMENT’S COMPLETION OF THE REDETERMINATION PROCESS.
3 (2) THIS SUBSECTION MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT THE
4 DEPARTMENT’S AUTHORITY OR DIMINISH THE DEPARTMENT’S RESPONSIBILITY TO
5 REINSTATE THE ELIGIBILITY OF AND THE PROVISION OF HOME– AND
6 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES TO A PROGRAM RECIPIENT WHO HAS BEEN
7 DISENROLLED FOR A REASON OTHER THAN A FAILURE BY THE DEPARTMENT TO
8 REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER.
9 (H) (G) SUBJECT TO FEDERAL APPROVAL, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
10 RESERVE A PORTION OF THE PARTICIPANT CAPACITY IN THE HOME– AND
11 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES WAIVER UNDER § 1915(C) OF THE FEDERAL SOCIAL
12 SECURITY ACT WAIVERS FOR SERVICES NEEDED BY PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WITH
13 DEVELOPMENTAL DISABILITIES WHO:
14 (1) WERE DISENROLLED FROM THE MARYLAND MEDICAID HOME
15 AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES WAIVER PROGRAM ON OR AFTER JANUARY 1,
16 2024;
17 (2) HAVE HAD PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY REINSTATED; AND
18 (3) HAVE REQUESTED THE REINSTATEMENT OF WAIVER SERVICES.
19 (I) THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT PLACE AN INDIVIDUAL ON A WAITING LIST
20 OR REQUIRE A NEW WAIVER APPLICATION IF THE DISENROLLMENT OF THE
21 INDIVIDUAL RESULTED FROM A DELAY OR AN ERROR BY THE DEPARTMENT.
22 (J) (H) (1) THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT PROCEDURALLY DISENROLL
23 AN INDIVIDUAL FROM THE PROGRAM OR HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES
24 SOLELY BASED ON MISSING DOCUMENTATION, A MISSING SIGNATURE, OR
25 INCOMPLETE INFORMATION UNLESS THE DEPARTMENT HAS:
26 (I) EXHAUSTED ALL EX PARTE VERIFICATION PROCESSES
27 REQUIRED UNDER 42 C.F.R. § 435.916;
28 (II) PROVIDED A CLEAR, SPECIFIC, AND ACCESSIBLE WRITTEN
29 NOTICE IDENTIFYING THE EXACT INFORMATION REQUIRED; AND
30 (III) PROVIDED THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT WITH A REASONABLE
31 OPPORTUNITY TO SUPPLY THE INFORMATION; AND

SENATE BILL 742 7
1 (IV) VERIFIED THAT THE INDIVIDUAL RECEIVED THE NOTICE
2 REQUIRED UNDER ITEM (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH AND DOCUMENTED THE
3 VERIFICATION.
4 (2) IF THE DEPARTMENT VIOLATES PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
5 SUBSECTION, A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES
6 SHALL CONTINUE WITHOUT INTERRUPTION.
7 (K) (I) IF THE DEPARTMENT DISENROLLS A PROGRAM RECIPIENT IN
8 VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
9 (1) AUTOMATICALLY REINSTATE PROGRAM AND HOME– AND
10 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES RETROACTIVE TO THE DATE OF DISENROLLMENT;
11 AND
12 (2) TREAT THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT AS CONTINUOUSLY ENROLLED.
13 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
14 as follows:
15 Article – Health – General
16 15–103.9.
17 (L) (J) (1) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, AND QUARTERLY
18 THEREAFTER, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
19 (I) SUBMIT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE
20 WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, A REPORT REGARDING
21 PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHO RECEIVE HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES;
22 AND
23 (II) POST EACH REPORT SUBMITTED UNDER ITEM (I) OF THIS
24 PARAGRAPH ON THE DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE.
25 (2) THE REPORTS REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
26 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
27 (I) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS FOR WHOM
28 A REDETERMINATION OF ELIGIBILITY WAS INITIATED;
29 (II) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS FOR WHOM
30 PROGRAM COVERAGE IS RENEWED;

8 SENATE BILL 742
1 (III) OF THE PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE ELIGIBILITY IS
2 RENEWED, THE TOTAL NUMBER WHOSE COVERAGE WAS RENEWED BASED ON AN EX
3 PARTE REDETERMINATION;
4 (IV) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE
5 ELIGIBILITY WAS REINSTATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (F) OF THIS
6 SECTION;
7 (IV) (V) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS
8 WHOSE ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED;
9 (V) (VI) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS
10 WHOSE ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED FOR PROCEDURAL REASONS;
11 (VII) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE
12 ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED DUE TO A FAILURE BY THE DEPARTMENT TO
13 REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER; AND
14 (VI) (VIII) THE MEAN AND MEDIAN PROCESSING TIMES FOR
15 REDETERMINATIONS OF ELIGIBILITY.
16 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
17 October 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 3 years and, at
18 the end of September 30, 2029, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the
19 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
20 Approved:
